	  <title>Matrix Shapes: Exercises</title>
	
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>How many nonzero entries can an <math>
                     <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                  </math> diagonal matrix have?</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <approach version="1">
			      <answer.exercise>
            <answer.exercise.block>
               <answer.exercise.block.body>
                  <para>
                     <para.body>An <math>
                           <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                        </math>-diagonal matrix can have at most <math>
                           <latex>n</latex>
                        </math> entries which are not <math>
                           <latex>0</latex>
                        </math>.</para.body>
                  </para>
               </answer.exercise.block.body>
            </answer.exercise.block>
         </answer.exercise>
			      <solution>
            <solution.body>
				           <para>
                  <para.body>A diagonal matrix is square shaped, and only entries in positions <math>
                        <latex>(i,i)</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>1\leq i\leq n</latex>
                     </math>, can be nonzero. There are precisely <math>
                        <latex>n</latex>
                     </math> such diagonal positions. Therefore such matrix can have at most <math>
                        <latex>n</latex>
                     </math> entries which are not <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>.</para.body>
               </para>
			         </solution.body>
         </solution>
		    </approach>
	  </exercise>
	
	  <exercise>
		    <problem>
         <problem.body>
			         <para>
               <para.body>How many nonzero entries can these upper triangular matrices have?</para.body>
            </para>
		       </problem.body>
      </problem>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(2,2)</latex>
                     </math> upper triangular matrices</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Such a matrix can have up to <math>
                              <latex>3</latex>
                           </math> nonzero entries</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(3,3)</latex>
                     </math> upper triangular matrices</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Such a matrix can have up to <math>
                              <latex>6</latex>
                           </math> nonzero entries</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(4,4)</latex>
                     </math> upper triangular matrices</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Such a matrix can have up to <math>
                              <latex>10</latex>
                           </math> nonzero entries</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
		    <part.exercise>
			      <problem>
            <problem.body>
               <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <math>
                        <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                     </math> upper triangular matrices</para.body>
               </para>
            </problem.body>
         </problem>
			      <approach version="1">
				        <answer.exercise>
               <answer.exercise.block>
                  <answer.exercise.block.body>
                     <para>
                        <para.body>Such a matrix can have up to <math>
                              <latex>\frac{1}{2}\cdot n\cdot (n+1)</latex>
                           </math> nonzero entries</para.body>
                     </para>
                  </answer.exercise.block.body>
               </answer.exercise.block>
            </answer.exercise>
				        <solution>
               <solution.body>
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Look at the columns of an upper triangular matrix of size <math>
                           <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                        </math>. The first column can contain <math>
                           <latex>1</latex>
                        </math> nonzero entry. The second column can contain up to <math>
                           <latex>2</latex>
                        </math> nonzero entries. The third column can contain up to <math>
                           <latex>3</latex>
                        </math> nonzero entries, and so on until, finally, the <math>
                           <latex>n</latex>
                        </math>-th column can contain up to <math>
                           <latex>n</latex>
                        </math> nonzero entries.</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>Therefore, an <math>
                           <latex>(n,n)</latex>
                        </math>-matrix can contain up to</para.body>
                  </para>
					
					             <math.display>
						               <latex>1+2+3+\cdots+n\ =\ \dfrac{n\cdot (n+1)}{2}</latex>
					             </math.display>
					
					             <para>
                     <para.body>nonzero entries.</para.body>
                  </para>
				           </solution.body>
            </solution>
			      </approach>
		    </part.exercise>
	  </exercise>
</exercise.pack>
